** May Sarton on the Cure for Despair and Solitude as the Seedbed of Self-=
Discovery (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/10/17/may-sarton-journal-of-=
a-solitude-depression/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])
------------------------------------------------------------

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393309282/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

=E2=80=9CA great deal of poetic work has arisen from various despairs=2C=
=E2=80=9D wrote Lou Andreas-Salom=C3=A9=2C the first woman psychoanalyst=
=2C in a consolatory letter (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/05/12/lou-=
andreas-salome-creative-block-rilke/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID=
]) to the poet Rainer Maria Rilke as he was wrestling with depression=2C n=
early a century before psychologists came to study the nonlinear relations=
hip between creativity and mental illness (https://www.brainpickings.org/2=
014/07/21/creativity-and-mental-illness/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UN=
IQID]) . A generation later=2C with an eye to what made Goethe a genius (h=
ttps://www.brainpickings.org/2016/10/10/humphrey-trevelyan-goethe-artist/?=
mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Humphrey Trevelyan argued that=
 great artists must have the courage to despair=2C that they =E2=80=9Cmust=
 be shaken by the naked truths that will not be comforted. This divine dis=
content=2C this disequilibrium=2C this state of inner tension is the sourc=
e of artistic energy.=E2=80=9D

Few artists have articulated the dance between this =E2=80=9Cdivine discon=
tent=E2=80=9D and creative fulfillment more memorably than the poet=2C nov=
elist=2C essayist=2C and diarist May Sarton (May 3=2C 1912=E2=80=93July 16=
=2C 1995). In her Journal of a Solitude (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos=
/ASIN/0393309282/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) (publ=
ic library (http://www.worldcat.org/title/journal-of-a-solitude/oclc/53230=
6&referer=3Dbrief_results?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) )=2C Sar=
ton records and reflects on her interior life in the course of one year=2C=
 her sixtieth=2C With remarkable candor and courage. Out of these twelve p=
rivate months arises the eternity of the human experience with its varied=
 universal capacities for astonishment and sorrow=2C hollowing despair and=
 creative vitality.

May Sarton

In an entry from September 15=2C 1972=2C Sarton writes:

It is raining. I look out on the maple=2C where a few leaves have turned y=
ellow=2C and listen to Punch=2C the parrot=2C talking to himself and to th=
e rain ticking gently against the windows. I am here alone for the first t=
ime in weeks=2C to take up my =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D life again at last. T=
hat is what is strange=E2=80=94that friends=2C even passionate love=2C are=
 not my real life unless there is time alone in which to explore and to di=
scover what is happening or has happened. Without the interruptions=2C nou=
rishing and maddening=2C this life would become arid. Yet I taste it fully=
 only when I am alone=E2=80=A6

She considers solitude as the seedbed of self-discovery:

For a long time now=2C every meeting with another human being has been a c=
ollision. I feel too much=2C sense too much=2C am exhausted by the reverbe=
rations after even the simplest conversation. But the deep collision is an=
d has been with my unregenerate=2C tormenting=2C and tormented self. I hav=
e written every poem=2C every novel=2C for the same purpose =E2=80=94 to f=
ind out what I think=2C to know where I stand.

[=E2=80=A6]

My need to be alone is balanced against my fear of what will happen when s=
uddenly I enter the huge empty silence if I cannot find support there. I g=
o up to Heaven and down to Hell in an hour=2C and keep alive only by impos=
ing upon myself inexorable routines.

Art by Sir Quentin Blake from Michael Rosen=E2=80=99s Sad Book (https://ww=
w.brainpickings.org/2015/08/25/michael-rosens-sad-book-quentin-blake/?mc_c=
id=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID])

In another journal entry penned three days later=2C in the grip of her rec=
urrent struggle with depression=2C Sarton revisits the question of the dif=
ficult=2C necessary self-confrontations that solitude makes possible:

The value of solitude =E2=80=94 one of its values =E2=80=94 is=2C of cours=
e=2C that there is nothing to cushion against attacks from within=2C just=
 as there is nothing to help balance at times of particular stress or depr=
ession. A few moments of desultory conversation =E2=80=A6 may calm an inne=
r storm. But the storm=2C painful as it is=2C might have had some truth in=
 it. So sometimes one has simply to endure a period of depression for what=
 it may hold of illumination if one can live through it=2C attentive to wh=
at it exposes or demands.

In a passage that calls to mind William Styron=E2=80=99s sobering account=
 of living with depression (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/09/depre=
ssion-william-styron-darkness-visible/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQ=
ID]) =2C Sarton adds:

The reasons for depression are not so interesting as the way one handles i=
t=2C simply to stay alive.

Perhaps Albert Camus was right in asserting that =E2=80=9Cthere is no love=
 of life without despair of life=2C=E2=80=9D (https://www.brainpickings.or=
g/2015/11/30/albert-camus-travel-lyrical-critical-essays/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e=
46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) but this is a truth hard to take in and even harde=
r to swallow when one is made tongueless by depression. In an entry from O=
ctober 6=2C still clawing her way out of the pit of darkness=2C Sarton con=
siders the only cure for despair she knows:

Does anything in nature despair except man? An animal with a foot caught i=
n a trap does not seem to despair. It is too busy trying to survive. It is=
 all closed in=2C to a kind of still=2C intense waiting. Is this a key? Ke=
ep busy with survival. Imitate the trees. Learn to lose in order to recove=
r=2C and remember that nothing stays the same for long=2C not even pain=2C=
 psychic pain. Sit it out. Let it all pass. Let it go.

By mid-October=2C Sarton has begun to emerge from the abyss and marvels at=
 the transformation in a beautiful testament to the finitude and transitor=
iness of all things=2C even the deepest-cutting and most all-consuming of=
 states:

I can hardly believe that relief from the anguish of these past months is=
 here to stay=2C but so far it does feel like a true change of mood =E2=80=
=94 or rather=2C a change of being where I can stand alone.

Echoing Virginia Woolf=E2=80=99s memorable insight into writing and self-d=
oubt (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/02/25/virginia-woolf-writing-self=
-doubt/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 the same self-do=
ubt with which Steinbeck=E2=80=99s diary is strewn (https://www.brainpicki=
ngs.org/2015/03/02/john-steinbeck-working-days/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =E2=80=94 Sarton considers the measure of success in creativ=
e work:

So much of my life here is precarious. I cannot always believe even in my=
 work. But I have come in these last days to feel again the validity of my=
 struggle here=2C that it is meaningful whether I ever =E2=80=9Csucceed=E2=
=80=9D as a writer or not=2C and that even its failures=2C failures of ner=
ve=2C failures due to a difficult temperament=2C can be meaningful. It is=
 an age where more and more human beings are caught up in lives where fewe=
r and fewer inward decisions can be made=2C where fewer and fewer real cho=
ices exist. The fact that a middle-aged=2C single woman=2C without any ves=
tige of family left=2C lives in this house in a silent village and is resp=
onsible only to her own soul means something. The fact that she is a write=
r and can tell where she is and what it is like on the pilgrimage inward c=
an be of comfort. It is comforting to know there are lighthouse keepers on=
 rocky islands along the coast. Sometimes=2C when I have been for a walk a=
fter dark and see my house lighted up=2C looking so alive=2C I feel
that my presence here is worth all the Hell.

Complement these particular passages of the wholly exquisite Journal of a=
 Solitude (http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0393309282/braipick-20?m=
c_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) with Tchaikovsky on depression and=
 finding beauty amid the wreckages of the soul (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2015/11/19/tchaikovsky-letters-depession/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C then revisit Louise Bourgeois on how solitude enriches c=
reative work (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/15/louise-bourgeois-so=
litude/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) and Elizabeth Bishop on wh=
y everyone needs at least one prolonged period of solitude in life (https:=
//www.brainpickings.org/2016/02/08/elizabeth-bishop-solitude/?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) .


