http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520285948/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Beyond the revelations of this particular city=2C the maps reveal the natu=
re of all cities as functions of human intention with its always dual and=
 often dueling capacities for good and evil=2C for revolution and repressi=
on=2C for power and prejudice=2C for creation and destruction. To map any=
 city is to present a polished mosaic of selective memory built atop the r=
ubble of selective forgetting. In reimagining the social and cultural land=
scape of New York=2C Solnit and Shapiro reclaim the unmapped territories o=
f being and the untold stories of beings marginalized by the dominant psyc=
hogeographies of their time =E2=80=94 from women to Native Americans to wi=
ldlife species.

Solnit writes in the introduction:

A city is a machine with innumerable parts made by the accumulation of hum=
an gestures=2C a colossal organism forever dying and being born=2C an ongo=
ing conflict between memory and erasure=2C a center for capital and for at=
tacks on capital=2C a rapture=2C a misery=2C a mystery=2C a conspiracy=2C=
 a destination and point of origin=2C a labyrinth in which some are lost a=
nd some find what they=E2=80=99re looking for=2C an argument about how to=
 live=2C and evidence that differences don=E2=80=99t always have to be res=
olved=2C though they may grace and grind against each other for centuries.

[=E2=80=A6]

Each of us is an atlas of sorts=2C already knowing how to navigate some po=
rtion of the world=2C containing innumerable versions of place as experien=
ce and desire and fear=2C as route and landmark and memory. So a city and=
 its citizens constitute a living library.

With an eye to the inherent incompleteness of any cartographic representat=
ion of a place as rife with infinite possibility as a city=2C Solnit adds:

Each of us grasps and inhabits only part of the pattern. The complexity be=
yond comprehension is one of the marvels of great cities=2C their inexhaus=
tible=2C ever-renewing mystery=E2=80=A6 Every city is many places; the old=
 woman and the young child do not live in the same city=2C and the rich an=
d the poor=2C the pedestrian and the wheelchair-bound=2C black and white i=
nhabit different but not completely separate realms.

[=E2=80=A6]

A city is not one or the other of these things but all of them=2C contradi=
ctions and collaborations and conflicts together=2C forever churning and s=
pitting out new possibilities.

Among the peculiarities of New York=2C a city that is at once a template a=
nd a glorious oddity=2C is the mismatch between its location and its signi=
ficance =E2=80=94 perched on the periphery of the country and hanging off=
 the very edge of the continent=2C it is nonetheless an epicenter of creat=
ive culture and intellectual life. In a passage that calls to mind Susan S=
ontag=E2=80=99s memorable words on the crucial difference between being in=
 the middle and being at the center (https://www.brainpickings.org/2014/06=
/24/susan-sontag-middle-center-jonathan-cott/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=
=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Solnit captures the centripetal force of this peripheral=
 city:

The opera diva from the rustic West at the center of Willa Cather=E2=80=99=
s novel The Song of the Lark leaves small-town Colorado for Chicago for he=
r first round of education as a musician=2C but she triumphed by becoming=
 a successful artist in New York=2C as Cather did herself (https://www.bra=
inpickings.org/2015/12/07/willa-cather-letters-writing/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46=
c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) for the last forty-one years of her life. There she=
 wrote vividly about the West=2C while living with her partner=2C editor E=
dith Lewis (https://www.brainpickings.org/2013/04/17/willa-cather-letters/=
?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C in the East=2C where a publis=
hing job had brought her and where privacy=2C tolerance=2C sophistication=
=2C maybe access to Europe and editors=2C seem to have kept her.

It=E2=80=99s a reverse of the old mythic westward migration for freedom=
 =E2=80=94 though it=E2=80=99s worth remembering that other New Yorkers le=
ft the city in search of liberation=2C whether it was the patrician Edith=
 Wharton checking out of the closed upper-class society she continued to w=
rite about or James Baldwin escaping American racism for a while (https://=
www.brainpickings.org/2016/04/04/james-baldwin-nikki-giovannis-dialogue/?m=
c_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) ... You could come to New York to a=
ppear or to disappear; the city accommodated all kinds of wishes.

[=E2=80=A6]

New York is a center that pulls people in and a centrifuge that spins them=
 out into the world.

Cather=2C Wharton=2C and Barnes are among the women depicted in one of the=
 most fetching maps in the atlas=2C City of Women=2C which reimagines the=
 iconic New York City subway map =E2=80=94 a feat of graphic design but a=
 failure of social justice=2C with its complacent abundance of stops named=
 after white men. In this alternative version=2C each stop on the city=E2=
=80=99s twenty-two subway lines is renamed after a notable woman who was b=
orn=2C lived=2C or made her name nearby.

Cartography: Molly Roy; subway route symbols =C2=A9 Metropolitan Transit A=
uthority

