NIQID]) across the river.)

Cartography: Molly Roy

Solnit=2C herself the daughter of a Jewish New Yorker mother=2C introduces=
 the map:

Stereotypes and generalizations generally precede discrimination. Often th=
ey depend on the belief that all members of the hated group have common ch=
aracteristics=2C so much so that you can punish any member for the sins al=
l members share. Except that they don=E2=80=99t. Categories are leaky=2C a=
nomalies often occur=2C and differences within groups can matter as much o=
r more than similarities. You could make this map=2C pointing up diversity=
=2C of any ethnic group=2C but we made it of Jews because New York has the=
 greatest concentration of Jews on earth outside Israel=2C and because the=
 word Jew contains a host of internal contradictions=2C from positions on=
 Israel and capitalism and religion to race and class. What can you say of=
 a group that=2C even within New York=2C ranges from Busy Siegel to Sammy=
 Davis Jr. to Ruth Bader Ginsburg to the Beastie Boys? Whether Judaism is=
 a culture=2C an ethnicity=2C or a religion is an unresolved question for=
 people who are good at questions=2C and even Judaism the
religion runs from the progressive inclusiveness of Chelsea=E2=80=99s quee=
r-friendly Congregation Beit Simchat Torah to the mysticism and strictures=
 of the Hasidic ranks of Williamsburg. What is a Jew? This is an explorati=
on without an answer=2C or with as many answers as there are Jews.

Riot! depicts the eruptions of unrest and revolution in =E2=80=9Ca city at=
 a simmer that boils over readily.=E2=80=9D

Cartography: Molly Roy; artwork: Thomas Nast=2C illustration of Draft Riot=
s=2C Harper=E2=80=99s Weekly=2C August 1=2C 1863

In the accompanying essay=2C Luc Sante makes clear that most of these upri=
sings sprang up when the systemic abuse and oppression of minorities reach=
ed a breaking point=2C from the Stonewall riots (https://www.brainpickings=
=2Eorg/2013/06/28/vintage-pride-parade/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) to the aftermath of Eric Garner=E2=80=99s murder in the hands of the N=
YPD. (I=E2=80=99m reminded here of Chinua Achebe=E2=80=99s astute observat=
ion (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/21/james-baldwin-chinua-achebe-=
art/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) that those who condemn someth=
ing as too political are simply those who see it as discordant with their=
 politics and who prefer the status quo undisturbed=2C so the very act of=
 labeling a civic event a =E2=80=9Criot=E2=80=9D can itself be a function=
 of the oppressive status quo.)

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520285948/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520285948/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

Indeed=2C dissent=2C difference=2C and divergent viewpoints are core to th=
e genome of the city=E2=80=99s spirit =E2=80=94 this city=2C as any great=
 city. These=2C after all=2C were the conditions that catalyzed the emerge=
nce of the revolutionary Vienna Circle (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016=
/09/20/janna-levin-a-madman-dreams-of-turing-machines/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c=
&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) in the early twentieth century=2C which forever chang=
ed the course of art=2C science=2C and philosophy. I recall a poignant pas=
sage of May Sarton=E2=80=99s journals (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/=
10/17/may-sarton-journal-of-a-solitude-depression/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_=
eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C in which she describes Dallas =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cjust=
 plain inhuman=2C too rich=2C too new=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 as a city of arti=
ficial beauty empty of poetry=2C where people are =E2=80=9Cstarved for a k=
ind of reality that does not exist in Neiman Marcus fur coats=2C in change=
s of fashion=2C in redecorating=2C=E2=80=9D where =E2=80=9Cunder the polit=
e small talk=2C one sensed nostalgia=2C the nostalgia of the bored child w=
ho does not know what he lacks=2C but knows he is being deprived of someth=
ing
essential to his well-being.=E2=80=9D Such homogeneity of privileged polit=
eness threatens to sap any city of its essential energy. With an eye to th=
ese forces =E2=80=9Cdriving diversity and complexity=E2=80=9D out of the c=
ity=2C Solnit asks:

What are cities when the qualities that have defined them are drowned in r=
ising tides of what we call wealth =E2=80=94 that increase in holdings for=
 some that increases scarcity=2C desperation=2C and exclusion for others?

The odd notion of the central city as a place where bohemia and dissent th=
rive has been withering away as cities become enclaves of the affluent and=
 the corporate =E2=80=94 or empty zones. Many of the condominiums and luxu=
ry apartments are often unoccupied=2C either because they=E2=80=99re not p=
rimary residences=2C or because they=E2=80=99re places to park money for t=
he transnational super-wealthy or their corporations.

Reflecting on a world where gentrification has inverted Langston Hughes=E2=
=80=99s lament about white flight (https://www.brainpickings.org/2016/09/2=
3/american-heartbreak-langston-hughes-reads/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D=
[UNIQID]) =2C Solnit adds:

The poor are pushed to the periphery=2C to the old suburbs=2C which fall i=
nto their own kind of decay. In the inner city the poor had access to shar=
ed resources like public pools and parks=2C to public transit=2C and to th=
e possibility of a collective power and civil society engagement that the=
 suburbs do not offer. There they become literally marginal.

[=E2=80=A6]

Cities are not over. But it=E2=80=99s hard not to fear that the great citi=
es of the North are never going to be what they were. Just as most have ca=
sed to be centers of industrial production=2C so they may cease to be cent=
ers of cultural production=2C at last with the intensity they once possess=
ed. Now they=E2=80=99re menaced by climate change=2C too. New York CIty=E2=
=80=99s coastline will be pummeled with hurricanes and blizzards; hotter=
=2C wetter weather will bring the kind of heat waves that tend to kill sen=
iors; food prices will likely rise=2C and climate refugees will become a n=
ew subpopulation. It=E2=80=99s impossible to say exactly what this city=2C=
 like other great cities ceasing to be what they were=2C will become.

Brooklyn Villages=2C laid out in the style of the first modern world map (=
https://www.brainpickings.org/2012/04/17/magnificent-maps-cartography-as-p=
ower-propaganda-and-art/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C plots=
 former Native American settlements=2C original Dutch and English villages=
=2C and Freedmen=E2=80=99s towns alongside contemporary housing complexes=
 and real estate developments. My own home nestles uncomfortably between a=
 onetime Ihretonga settlement and the aptly named =E2=80=9CRapacious Devel=
opers Village=E2=80=9D of today.

Cartography: Molly Roy; artwork: Hannah Chalew

