And yet the stories told in this atlas =E2=80=94 for every map is a story=
 =E2=80=94 are decidedly redemptive. They offer considered counterpoints w=
hich=2C in exposing the fragments of our sociocultural brokenness=2C compo=
se us closer to wholeness.

Noting the =E2=80=9Cspecial incandescent joy=E2=80=9D with which we humans=
 respond to maps=2C Solnit examines her criteria for these cartographic re=
demptions:

Maps demand work=2C and this kind of cerebral work can be exhilarating.

By a good map I mean an aesthetic one=2C a map that is an invitation to th=
e imagination=2C a map that offers a fresh view of the familiar or an intr=
oduction to the unfamiliar or finds the latter in the former. If every map=
 is a story=2C most of them are mysteries that invite you to solve them wh=
ile remaining forever unsolved=2C in that they indicate more =E2=80=94 mor=
e past=2C more future=2C more adventures=2C more travels. They have an ope=
nness=2C indicating more than they depict.

Maps=2C Solnit reminds us=2C are above all exercises in editing=2C both co=
nscious and unconscious:

A map can trace one story=2C though it often portrays the coexistences of=
 many stories in relation to each other. It can show how the physical=2C e=
conomic=2C visual=2C and social landscape can shape those stories=2C letti=
ng some bloom=2C grinding out others. Multiple stories in spatial relation=
 become the geosocial constellations of our lives=E2=80=A6

A map is a proposition: here is what this place is=2C or was=2C or will be=
=2E Most contemporary maps are predictable propositions: here are streets an=
d freeways and also parking and maybe shopping or subway lines. But imagin=
ation can always go beyond what even the most quotidian map shows. You kno=
w that when you exit the Columbus Circle subway stop=2C Central Park will=
 be there=2C and that may evoke majestic trees or strolls or memories of c=
rimes or performances; or the Mets-Willets Point subway stop in Queens on=
 the 7 may make you think about the Unisphere or Venus and Serena Williams=
 at the U.S. Open or when the ash heaps described in The Great Gatsby were=
 nearby.

We furnish maps with imagination; they offer us rooms to furnish thus. Eve=
n the most straightforward map is an invitation=E2=80=A6

In orienting oneself in this atlas =E2=80=94 and orient is a fitting word=
 in speaking of New York=2C for it comes from the Latin oriens=2C meaning=
 to find east by looking for the rising sun =E2=80=94 one is invited to fa=
thom the many New Yorks hidden from history=E2=80=99s eye. But=2C more tha=
n that=2C the atlas stands as a reminder that maps make cities as much as=
 cities make maps=2C and that humans make meaning through how we build and=
 map and live our cities and our stories.

Undergirding the project is a certain countercultural quality in calling o=
n paper maps to nurture us with richer meaning in an age when digital maps=
 feed us mere information. In a sentiment that harkens back to her beautif=
ul meditation on how modern technology is changing our experience of time=
 and place (https://www.brainpickings.org/2015/11/23/rebecca-solnit-encycl=
opedia-of-trouble-and-spaciousness-2/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQI=
D]) =2C Solnit writes:

Digital devices tend to offload knowledge from brains to machines=2C promi=
se us that our ignorance will be adequate because machines will augment us=
=2E All recording technologies do this=2C but paper maps have a way of trans=
ferring their data to your mind=2C so that you become the map. You don=E2=
=80=99t become the phone. Expertise about place never becomes yours with t=
he digital devices=2C but it often does with paper=2C which=2C paradoxical=
ly enough=2C makes paper a more fluid interactive technology.

http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520285948/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df47=
6b8e46c&mc_eid=3D[UNIQID]

In the remainder of the thoroughly terrific Nonstop Metropolis (http://www=
=2Eamazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0520285948/braipick-20?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc=
_eid=3D[UNIQID]) =2C Solnit=2C Shapiro=2C and their venerable stable of w=
riters go on to celebrate =E2=80=9Cthe complexity=2C the layers and tangle=
s=2C the cross-pollinations and conflicts=2C the hidden and overlooked=2C=
 the ugly and beautiful=E2=80=9D aspects of the city. Complement it with p=
ioneering photographer Beatrice Abbott=E2=80=99s stunning black-and-white=
 portraits of New York=E2=80=99s changing face (https://www.brainpickings.=
org/2012/11/12/changing-new-york-berenice-abbott/?mc_cid=3Df476b8e46c&mc_e=
id=3D[UNIQID]) and Jack Kerouac=E2=80=99s tour of the unseen New York (ht=
tps://www.brainpickings.org/2013/06/13/jack-kerouac-lonesome-traveler-new-=
